-- Canada Stocks Snap 3-Day Gain as IMF Cuts China Growth Estimate
-- B y   E r i c   L a m
-- 2013-05-29T14:02:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-29/canada-stocks-snap-3-day-gain-as-imf-cuts-china-growth-estimate.html
Canadian  stocks  fell, snapping a
three-day rally, after the International Monetary Fund cut its
projections for economic growth in  China , the nation’s second-largest trading partner.  Copper Mountain Mining Corp. (CUM)  declined 2.9 percent as the
price of the industrial metal retreated. Enbridge Inc. and
Savanna Energy Services Corp. lost at least 0.7 percent as oil
fell. Bank of Montreal, Canada’s fourth-biggest lender, dropped
2.2 percent after second-quarter profit missed expectations. BRP
Inc., maker of Ski-Doo snowmobiles and three-wheeled
motorcycles, jumped 16 percent from its initial offering price
in its trading debut today.  The  Standard & Poor’s/TSX Composite Index (SPTSX)  lost 40.82
points, or 0.3 percent, to 12,709.70 at 9:59 a.m. in Toronto.
The index has gained 2.2 percent this year.  China, the world’s biggest consumer of most commodities,
will grow 7.75 percent this year and next, the IMF said today.
In April, the IMF forecast growth of 8 percent this year and 8.2
percent expansion in 2014. Raw-materials and energy companies
account for about 39 percent of  Canada ’s benchmark equity gauge.  In a separate release, the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development said China, which isn’t a member of
the OECD, will grow 7.8 percent in 2013 and 8.4 percent in 2014.
China’s economy grew 7.8 percent in 2012.  To contact the reporter on this story:
